From: HighTide <noreply@local>
Date: Thu, 29 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] odb: dbNet::getFirstOutput don't skip clocked OUTPUTs (driver)

Upstream OpenROAD PR #10549 (merged as cd4f5041).  Carried locally
until the bazel-orfs OpenROAD pin advances past that commit.

dbNet::getFirstOutput() unconditionally skipped iterms with
isClocked() == true.  isClocked() returns true when the iterm's MTerm
has SigType::CLOCK, which is the correct flag for INPUT clock-sinks
(flop CLK pins) but ALSO for OUTPUT clock-source pins like a macro's
clock-output (liberty `direction: output; clock: true;`) or a
clock-buffer output.  The skip dropped the actual driver of any
clock net whose source pin is tagged `clock: true`, returning
nullptr.

TritonCTS.cpp:1295 then falls into the bterm branch, fails again
(when the clock is driven by an internal macro pin rather than a
top-level port), and emits

  [INFO CTS-0122] Clock net "<net>" is skipped for CTS because it is
  not connected to any output instance pin or input block terminal.

No clock tree gets built; every flop on that domain is reached only
by naked placement+routing wire delay — large, unbalanced skew, and
a flood of unfixable hold violations.  Verified on litepci sys_clk
(driven by PCIe hard-IP user_clk, ~12k flops, ~9 ns skew before
the fix, normal CTS-balanced numbers after).

Fix: drop the isClocked() skip entirely.  The existing
`getIoType() != dbIoType::OUTPUT` continue immediately below already
filters clock sinks (they are INPUT pins), so the isClocked() skip
was redundant for sinks and actively wrong for the legitimate
clock-source OUTPUT.  isClocked() is true for both ends of a clock
net; only direction distinguishes source from sink.
---
 src/odb/src/db/dbNet.cpp | 4 ----
 1 file changed, 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/odb/src/db/dbNet.cpp b/src/odb/src/db/dbNet.cpp
--- a/src/odb/src/db/dbNet.cpp
+++ b/src/odb/src/db/dbNet.cpp
@@ -1264,10 +1264,6 @@ dbITerm* dbNet::getFirstOutput() const
       continue;
     }

-    if (tr->isClocked()) {
-      continue;
-    }
-
     if (tr->getIoType() != dbIoType::OUTPUT) {
       continue;
     }
